@AfzalMirza51 Ameen, JazakAllah khair for your kind words. Please remember the deceased and his family in your prayers as well
@LAhmad08 Thank you. I hope whoever reads it, appreciates first aid courses and books one for themselves!

But if I hadn't taken any first aid courses.. I would have no idea what to do, just like all those people around him.

So I ask you, please look up first aid courses around you and attend them! If any of those people had started CPR earlier, it would have helped so much more. /10

So today was the first time I called myself a #pharmacist. The training I undertook was useful. The #FirstAid courses I've been to were extremely useful. Nothing could have prepared for the scene I encountered. There was nothing easy and nothing nice about it. /9

I started CPR. By this time the @MPSTooting came. They took over and bought an AED too. Soon, #paramedics arrived as well and started doing all they can. 
It was amazing to see them all trying to save this man..
As far as I could tell.. Until we left they hadn't found a pulse. /8

The collapsed man has no pulse and is not breathing and has obstructed airways which I've tried to clear as much as possible. By now, I had asked the people around me to help straighten him so I could start #CPR. /7

While I was trying to find out all of this, people kept screaming 'don't move him! Don't touch him!' 
That was the first time I had to say 'I am a pharmacist, I'm just trying to help!' 
I took over the 999 call and let them know, hi my name is Daniya. I am a pharmacist. /6

I immediately started running through the first aid I had been taught by @stjohnambulance and first aid as part of my #PreRegYear. His airway was blocked by his tongue and vomit, he wasn't breathing and he didn't have a pulse. 
/5

The man was collapsed against a wall, his arms were in an awkward position as he had fallen, he had vomited and lost bladder control. He wasn't responding to any stimuli. 
A woman in the crowd was on the phone to the emergency services, trying to get an ambulance. /4

While she was saying this, she was still driving albeit very slowly.
I kept looking at the man and I could tell something just wasn't right. 
I told her to stop and let me out. 

I ran out of the car, to the man. The closer I got, I could tell something was seriously wrong. /3

I didn't work a shift today either, but I still called myself a pharmacist. 
My mum and I were driving past a road when we saw a collapsed man with people milling around him and a woman shouting 'my husband, my husband!' 
My mum said I know that woman! I wonder what happened. /2

I am a newly qualified #pharmacist and I will be going on the register on the 1st of September, but today I did my first act as a pharmacist. Until that moment, I had hesitated to call myself a pharmacist. After all.. I hadn't even worked one shift since qualifying. /1
